00:03:48.960 --> 00:03:52.940
So Paul, why don't we start
just with a little bit

00:03:52.940 --> 00:03:55.100
of background
about ebola itself.

00:03:55.100 --> 00:03:58.880
So, tell us what are the
most important things

00:03:58.880 --> 00:04:00.260
that we need to know.

00:04:00.260 --> 00:04:06.160
Why is this epidemic scaring
people like no other,

00:04:06.160 --> 00:04:07.620
and where do you see it headed?

00:04:09.482 --> 00:04:11.440
PAUL FARMER: You know,
one of the things that's

00:04:11.440 --> 00:04:15.440
important to know
is-- you don't have

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:18.940
to know the kind of virus it is.

00:04:18.940 --> 00:04:21.480
That's not that important.

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:23.000
What you need to
know is I'm pretty

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:27.225
sure we know where it comes
from and how it's transmitted.

00:04:27.225 --> 00:04:30.470
It's a zoonosis,
as everybody knows.

00:04:32.930 --> 00:04:34.270
But what's happened--

00:04:34.270 --> 00:04:35.540
JACQUELINE FULLER: Meaning
it comes from animals.

00:04:35.540 --> 00:04:36.998
PAUL FARMER: It
comes from animals.

00:04:36.998 --> 00:04:38.410
It jumps from animals to humans.

00:04:38.410 --> 00:04:42.590
And what happened-- and this has
happened with every outbreak--

00:04:42.590 --> 00:04:48.310
is that primates,
human or nonhuman,

00:04:48.310 --> 00:04:50.220
are not the host, right?

00:04:50.220 --> 00:04:52.222
We're accidental hosts.

00:04:52.222 --> 00:04:53.680
And so there's a
lot of speculation

00:04:53.680 --> 00:04:55.055
that you've probably
already read

00:04:55.055 --> 00:04:59.300
about this that it's from
eating bushmeat, or a fruit

00:04:59.300 --> 00:05:03.520
bat with butterfingers-- very
clumsy fruit bat drops a piece

00:05:03.520 --> 00:05:07.420
of half eaten
fruit, and some kid.

00:05:07.420 --> 00:05:11.300
Wherever it came from, that's
not what's going on now.

00:05:11.300 --> 00:05:15.580
What's going on now is person
to person transmission because

00:05:15.580 --> 00:05:19.980
of a failed health
care system or systems,

00:05:19.980 --> 00:05:21.690
because it's a region, right?

00:05:24.760 --> 00:05:25.510
That's one thing.

00:05:28.010 --> 00:05:30.170
And there are other ways
it could be transmitted.

00:05:30.170 --> 00:05:31.410
It's person to person.

00:05:31.410 --> 00:05:35.320
When you hear about
burials or funeral rituals,

00:05:35.320 --> 00:05:38.010
still, that's person
to person transmission.

00:05:38.010 --> 00:05:41.270
The virus can be excreted
after someone dies-- is

00:05:41.270 --> 00:05:42.650
excreted and infectious.

00:05:44.380 --> 00:05:46.600
But as far as we know,
it's not airborne.

00:05:47.720 --> 00:05:50.835
It's spread through
infected secretions.

00:05:52.640 --> 00:05:56.690
Second point I think I would
just move up on the list

00:05:56.690 --> 00:06:01.820
is that you hear that the case
fatality rate is really high,

00:06:01.820 --> 00:06:03.449
but what does that mean?

00:06:03.449 --> 00:06:05.865
It means that a lot of people
who get the virus are dying.

00:06:07.390 --> 00:06:10.730
But it doesn't mean
that they should die.

00:06:10.730 --> 00:06:14.740
And just for the
sake of argument,

00:06:14.740 --> 00:06:18.110
I've been saying-- again, just
for the sake of argument-- what

00:06:18.110 --> 00:06:22.520
if it's not the case fatality
rate that should be 90%,

00:06:22.520 --> 00:06:24.550
it's the survival rate?

00:06:24.550 --> 00:06:27.350
And if we had that
as our supposition,

00:06:27.350 --> 00:06:31.800
then we'd say, as you
guys say at Google,

00:06:31.800 --> 00:06:35.490
how are we going to work
against this goal or this plan?

00:06:35.490 --> 00:06:37.440
And if the goal or
plan is let's make sure

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:40.120
everybody survives,
then we have to work

00:06:40.120 --> 00:06:43.600
really hard to make sure that
people are diagnosed early,

00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:45.430
that they're given proper care.

00:06:45.430 --> 00:06:49.690
Because even without a specific
therapy in anti-viral--

00:06:49.690 --> 00:06:52.820
and there are people-- I don't
want to talk about this--

00:06:52.820 --> 00:06:59.172
we do have treatments for
people who present very often

00:06:59.172 --> 00:07:00.630
in what's called
hypovolemic shock.

00:07:01.980 --> 00:07:06.920
So when you have ebola, some
of the first things that happen

00:07:06.920 --> 00:07:09.310
are abdominal pain, fever.

00:07:09.310 --> 00:07:11.900
Even with a fever, you
start losing fluids.

00:07:11.900 --> 00:07:16.300
And then you have
vomiting, diarrhea,

00:07:16.300 --> 00:07:19.840
and just as with any other
cause of those symptoms,

00:07:19.840 --> 00:07:22.750
you're losing electrolytes,
you're losing fluids,

00:07:22.750 --> 00:07:24.710
and the treatment is
fluid resuscitation.

00:07:26.270 --> 00:07:30.370
And any American emergency
room can do that.

00:07:30.370 --> 00:07:33.625
Even when someone can't
drink, oral rehydration,

00:07:33.625 --> 00:07:34.250
like Pedialyte.

00:07:35.790 --> 00:07:38.150
So we've got to
remember that we're

00:07:38.150 --> 00:07:44.484
losing people who-- there's not
a lot of T in the ETU-- ebola

00:07:44.484 --> 00:07:45.150
treatment units.

00:07:46.280 --> 00:07:47.480
That's the second thing.

00:07:47.480 --> 00:07:48.940
I'm only putting
it in this order

00:07:48.940 --> 00:07:51.180
because these are things
I'd like everybody to know.

00:07:52.900 --> 00:07:56.645
The health systems issue,
that we've got to do better.

00:07:58.430 --> 00:08:04.430
And just to throw
out another one,

00:08:04.430 --> 00:08:09.566
now there's finally attention
being turned to ebola.

00:08:09.566 --> 00:08:11.190
We should have done
it a long time ago.

00:08:11.190 --> 00:08:14.170
I don't know if my friend
Dan Kelly's in the room yet,

00:08:14.170 --> 00:08:17.260
but we were in
Sierra Leone, where

00:08:17.260 --> 00:08:20.590
he's worked for a long
time, in early June.

00:08:20.590 --> 00:08:24.100
Ebola had already
crashed into the city,

00:08:24.100 --> 00:08:25.770
and it's never done that before.

00:08:25.770 --> 00:08:28.801
It's been an isolated
outbreak, rural areas.

00:08:28.801 --> 00:08:29.800
That's where it started.

00:08:29.800 --> 00:08:32.699
But once it gets into
the health care system--

00:08:32.699 --> 00:08:35.240
Here's the third thing that I
think is worth keeping in mind.

00:08:37.047 --> 00:08:38.255
It's a disease of caregivers.

00:08:40.210 --> 00:08:43.990
Not just doctors--
nurses, nurses' aides,

00:08:43.990 --> 00:08:46.980
but who does the
majority of caregiving?

00:08:48.709 --> 00:08:49.750
JACQUELINE FULLER: Women.

00:08:49.750 --> 00:08:50.820
PAUL FARMER: Women.

00:08:50.820 --> 00:08:52.090
Your mom.

00:08:52.090 --> 00:08:52.690
Women.

00:08:52.690 --> 00:08:55.480
Women-- your mom, your
sister, your aunt.

00:08:55.480 --> 00:08:59.530
So even the story
from Dallas-- and it

00:08:59.530 --> 00:09:01.700
sounds to me like
the Good Samaritan.

00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:03.010
That's the way I read.

00:09:03.010 --> 00:09:09.650
Some guy trying to help a
pregnant woman who has ebola.

00:09:09.650 --> 00:09:13.270
And so those are three things
that just wouldn't come up

00:09:13.270 --> 00:09:15.320
on the first blush
that I think it would

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:18.460
be good to get into
popular consciousness.

00:09:18.460 --> 00:09:19.850
There's a lot we can do.

00:09:19.850 --> 00:09:22.940
This is not a new kind of
spread, as far as we can tell.

00:09:22.940 --> 00:09:24.680
We've got to protect
our caregivers.

00:09:24.680 --> 00:09:25.700
JACQUELINE FULLER: OK.

00:09:25.700 --> 00:09:27.650
And then just to set
the scene a little bit--

00:09:27.650 --> 00:09:29.790
some people might not
have the full context.

00:09:29.790 --> 00:09:30.940
You mentioned Sierra Leone.

00:09:30.940 --> 00:09:32.481
I was there a couple
years ago, and I

00:09:32.481 --> 00:09:36.020
remember I met the
only pediatrician

00:09:36.020 --> 00:09:37.480
in all of Sierra Leone.

00:09:37.480 --> 00:09:39.680
I mean, so you're
talking about a country

00:09:39.680 --> 00:09:43.270
where the health system
is already pretty fragile.

00:09:44.900 --> 00:09:46.980
And then something
like this hits.

00:09:46.980 --> 00:09:52.060
So maybe a word about how this
is impacting the health system.

00:09:52.060 --> 00:09:54.080
What response is in place?

00:09:54.080 --> 00:09:54.979
What can we do?

00:09:54.979 --> 00:09:57.020
PAUL FARMER: Well, as you
know, Jackie, concision

00:09:57.020 --> 00:09:58.830
is not my strong suit.

00:09:58.830 --> 00:10:01.490
But I will say a
word, and that is, it

00:10:01.490 --> 00:10:07.060
has already made the
health system fall apart.

00:10:07.060 --> 00:10:09.385
So that is also a done deal.

00:10:09.385 --> 00:10:13.330
The epidemic's
out, and it already

00:10:13.330 --> 00:10:15.872
took down the health system--
in Sierra Leone and in Liberia.

00:10:15.872 --> 00:10:18.288
JACQUELINE FULLER: So that
means that people with malaria,

00:10:18.288 --> 00:10:20.830
people with road accidents-- I
mean, it's cascading effects.

00:10:20.830 --> 00:10:21.490
PAUL FARMER: That's right.

00:10:21.490 --> 00:10:21.990
Exactly.

00:10:21.990 --> 00:10:24.340
And I think the same
is true of Guinea.

00:10:24.340 --> 00:10:29.380
I haven't been there, but
talking to Guinean officials,

00:10:29.380 --> 00:10:30.880
I think they'd say
the same thing.

00:10:30.880 --> 00:10:33.610
It's having a very adverse--

00:10:33.610 --> 00:10:36.720
The majority of ebola
victims won't have ebola.

00:10:37.960 --> 00:10:43.680
They'll have malaria, obstructed
labor, some other problems

00:10:43.680 --> 00:10:47.110
that they would have
ordinarily had taken on.

00:10:47.110 --> 00:10:51.120
So that means that our work
in emergency response--

00:10:51.120 --> 00:10:53.550
our collective work--
has to be linked

00:10:53.550 --> 00:10:55.930
to rebuilding that system,
and to strengthening

00:10:55.930 --> 00:10:57.330
local capacity.

00:10:57.330 --> 00:10:59.510
Yesterday-- a lot of you
know Larry Brilliant.

00:11:01.400 --> 00:11:04.650
Doctor Larry Brilliant, who's
now at Skoll Global Threats.

00:11:04.650 --> 00:11:08.450
But we were at a
conference, and he said,

00:11:08.450 --> 00:11:09.535
outbreaks are inevitable.

00:11:10.750 --> 00:11:12.275
Pandemics are optional.

00:11:13.660 --> 00:11:15.760
And that is pretty pithy, right?

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:21.860
Because you have to miss
all these chances to have

00:11:21.860 --> 00:11:23.330
a pandemic like this.

00:11:23.330 --> 00:11:26.435
And once it's in the global
economy, where people

00:11:26.435 --> 00:11:29.127
move around, it's
really harder to stop.

00:11:29.127 --> 00:11:31.460
JACQUELINE FULLER: Well, maybe
just expand on that a bit

00:11:31.460 --> 00:11:33.751
because, I think for folks
outside of the public health

00:11:33.751 --> 00:11:37.120
world, even understanding an
outbreak versus an epidemic

00:11:37.120 --> 00:11:40.640
versus a pandemic and the
impact that that can have,

00:11:40.640 --> 00:11:43.700
both in terms of morbidity,
mortality, people getting

00:11:43.700 --> 00:11:47.760
sick and dying, but also
economic impact on a region.

00:11:47.760 --> 00:11:51.340
So right now, we're looking
at while the official numbers

00:11:51.340 --> 00:11:53.780
of confirmed are only
about 7,000, right?

00:11:53.780 --> 00:11:56.650
But the estimate
is that it's just

00:11:56.650 --> 00:11:59.200
tens of thousands unreported.

00:11:59.200 --> 00:12:01.480
PAUL FARMER: We know that
the doubling time just using

00:12:01.480 --> 00:12:06.030
reported cases-- and again, I'm
sure this is obvious to all you

00:12:06.030 --> 00:12:10.250
nerds out there-- that
reporting capacity is

00:12:10.250 --> 00:12:11.940
related to health
systems, right?

00:12:11.940 --> 00:12:13.240
Strengthening.

00:12:13.240 --> 00:12:21.550
I was recently in rural
Liberia, and talking to a health

00:12:21.550 --> 00:12:23.310
official, and
there are very few.

00:12:23.310 --> 00:12:27.030
It's a thin-- although
they had stood up an effort

00:12:27.030 --> 00:12:29.840
beginning in March, even
out in the rural areas.

00:12:29.840 --> 00:12:37.030
And I was asking to figure
out the diagnostic capacity,

00:12:37.030 --> 00:12:39.130
is their [INAUDIBLE]
of fever here?

00:12:39.130 --> 00:12:43.280
And because I knew it's the same
forest where it is elsewhere.

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:44.610
And the answer was no.

00:12:44.610 --> 00:12:47.010
But what she really meant
is, we don't have a lab.

00:12:48.110 --> 00:12:50.980
So there is this
problem also of, well,

00:12:50.980 --> 00:12:55.540
what fraction of the cases are
reported, as you just said.

00:12:55.540 --> 00:13:00.030
And the modeling
exercises, as I'm

00:13:00.030 --> 00:13:02.590
sure people saw last week--
some of them are pretty grim.

00:13:02.590 --> 00:13:03.590
JACQUELINE FULLER: Yeah.

00:13:03.590 --> 00:13:04.520
PAUL FARMER: But
if you were talking

00:13:04.520 --> 00:13:05.936
about a more than
a million cases,

00:13:05.936 --> 00:13:08.090
you're also talking about
inaction and failure.

00:13:08.090 --> 00:13:09.600
And I think we could stop that.

00:13:09.600 --> 00:13:10.599
JACQUELINE FULLER: Yeah.

00:13:10.599 --> 00:13:12.150
What do you think
is-- just so we

00:13:12.150 --> 00:13:16.360
can get our hands around
how bad it might get.

00:13:16.360 --> 00:13:19.470
So now the deaths are
in the thousands--

00:13:19.470 --> 00:13:24.020
maybe 4,000 or 5,000 infections,
maybe in the tens of thousands.

00:13:24.020 --> 00:13:28.890
But predictions that infections
could go up in the millions.

00:13:28.890 --> 00:13:30.332
It could spread beyond that.

00:13:30.332 --> 00:13:31.790
What do you think
what is the worst

00:13:31.790 --> 00:13:35.370
case if we don't do what
we need to do and can do?

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:40.210
PAUL FARMER: Well, worst
case is really bad.

00:13:40.210 --> 00:13:42.540
And you asked me
to define outbreak.

00:13:42.540 --> 00:13:49.740
I mean, an outbreak-- this was
Larry's point-- zoonoses cause

00:13:49.740 --> 00:13:51.650
outbreaks, because
there's contact,

00:13:51.650 --> 00:13:53.950
and there's a lot of it,
between animals and humans.

00:13:53.950 --> 00:13:56.690
By the way, the humans are
winning, as many of you

00:13:56.690 --> 00:14:00.400
know-- meaning the animals
are not doing so hot.

00:14:01.690 --> 00:14:03.120
And that isn't because of ebola.

00:14:04.900 --> 00:14:06.980
That would be because of us.

00:14:06.980 --> 00:14:11.730
So an outbreak is
just a general term.

00:14:13.020 --> 00:14:16.680
You can have an outbreak
of two cases, right?

00:14:19.030 --> 00:14:21.600
I would say that this has
never really happened before.

00:14:21.600 --> 00:14:23.770
I mean, it's easy to say
it's never happened before.

00:14:23.770 --> 00:14:26.160
But to move into
this part of Africa,

00:14:26.160 --> 00:14:30.850
into cities, into the health
care system-- a lot of that

00:14:30.850 --> 00:14:34.430
is new at that level.

00:14:34.430 --> 00:14:35.020
All of it.

00:14:35.020 --> 00:14:37.020
JACQUELINE FULLER: Because
usually the outbreaks

00:14:37.020 --> 00:14:38.870
are closer to the bush.

00:14:38.870 --> 00:14:41.340
PAUL FARMER: Or they
also have been associated

00:14:41.340 --> 00:14:43.930
with poor infection
control practices.

00:14:43.930 --> 00:14:46.990
The first outbreak,
for example, ran right

00:14:46.990 --> 00:14:49.280
through a mission
hospital, killing

00:14:49.280 --> 00:14:51.935
the nurses and the
nuns and the patients.

00:14:53.130 --> 00:14:56.410
And so this is how it started.

00:14:56.410 --> 00:14:58.500
But it was contained.

00:14:58.500 --> 00:15:01.750
And this time, it
hasn't been contained.

00:15:01.750 --> 00:15:04.640
And to get back to the
economic question-- again,

00:15:04.640 --> 00:15:08.440
this is all over my
pay grade, or out

00:15:08.440 --> 00:15:10.080
of my field of expertise.

00:15:10.080 --> 00:15:13.000
Actually, this is Dan
Kelley, who just came in,

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:14.477
who I was just talking about.

00:15:18.780 --> 00:15:24.280
Even now, with the number
of cases that are reported,

00:15:24.280 --> 00:15:26.800
the economic impact is
already quite palpable.

00:15:26.800 --> 00:15:27.841
JACQUELINE FULLER: Right.

00:15:27.841 --> 00:15:33.820
PAUL FARMER: Because air travel,
ports, cross border trade,

00:15:33.820 --> 00:15:35.060
and tourism.

00:15:35.372 --> 00:15:36.580
JACQUELINE FULLER: Decimated.

00:15:36.580 --> 00:15:36.930
Yeah.

00:15:36.930 --> 00:15:38.790
PAUL FARMER: They've
already badly affected.

00:15:38.790 --> 00:15:40.831
JACQUELINE FULLER: Center
for Global Developments

00:15:40.831 --> 00:15:44.270
got some good graphs on that in
terms of the aversion effect.

00:15:44.270 --> 00:15:47.230
That is, not even just
direct loss from trade,

00:15:47.230 --> 00:15:49.670
but aversion-- people just
avoiding the entire region,

00:15:49.670 --> 00:15:52.590
and what that can do to
entire regional economies.

00:15:54.250 --> 00:15:57.390
PAUL FARMER: So I think
we're already in trouble.

00:15:57.390 --> 00:16:00.300
The question is just,
how do we get out?

00:16:00.300 --> 00:16:03.070
I mean, as a species,
obviously, I'm

00:16:03.070 --> 00:16:08.860
all for thinking this is
our collective problem.

00:16:08.860 --> 00:16:12.570
And I'm also happy that,
as far as I can tell,

00:16:12.570 --> 00:16:16.870
the people in charge in
those countries have said,

00:16:16.870 --> 00:16:17.990
we want help.

00:16:18.812 --> 00:16:19.770
JACQUELINE FULLER: Yes.

00:16:19.770 --> 00:16:21.120
PAUL FARMER: And that
doesn't always happen.

00:16:21.120 --> 00:16:21.350
JACQUELINE FULLER: No.

00:16:21.350 --> 00:16:22.933
There's a lot more
openness than we've

00:16:22.933 --> 00:16:24.310
seen with some other outbreaks.

00:16:24.310 --> 00:16:27.300
So, all right-- one last
question in the how bad is it,

00:16:27.300 --> 00:16:28.550
or how bad is it going to get?

00:16:28.550 --> 00:16:30.466
And then we'll switch
to solutions, I promise.

00:16:31.200 --> 00:16:33.950
So we saw the first apparent
case in the US Tuesday.

00:16:36.850 --> 00:16:41.340
Should we be worried in the
US or other developed nations?

00:16:41.340 --> 00:16:44.070
Do you see this
spreading in Europe?

00:16:44.070 --> 00:16:45.060
Asia?

00:16:45.060 --> 00:16:47.949
PAUL FARMER: I see it coming
to Europe, but not spreading.

00:16:47.949 --> 00:16:49.490
I see it coming to
the United States.

00:16:49.490 --> 00:16:55.950
Well, in fact, last week,
I got to play Cassandra.

00:16:55.950 --> 00:16:59.640
I was just saying on CNN--
first of all, they put in a room

00:16:59.640 --> 00:17:02.170
where I was supposed to
be doing a talk show,

00:17:02.170 --> 00:17:05.279
and I'm the only human in there,
looking around and saying,

00:17:05.279 --> 00:17:05.779
hello?

00:17:05.779 --> 00:17:06.279
Hello?

00:17:07.609 --> 00:17:08.859
50 minutes.

00:17:08.859 --> 00:17:10.319
No human.

00:17:10.319 --> 00:17:11.800
Anyway, I said, OK, all right.

00:17:11.800 --> 00:17:12.330
I did it.

00:17:12.330 --> 00:17:12.830
I confess.

00:17:14.420 --> 00:17:21.650
But when this disembodied figure
came on the camera and said,

00:17:21.650 --> 00:17:24.150
well, is this going to come to
the United States and Europe?

00:17:24.150 --> 00:17:25.829
I said, well, sure.

00:17:25.829 --> 00:17:28.250
Because, again, it's
a global economy.

00:17:28.250 --> 00:17:32.470
But I agree with the CDC
director Tom Friedan.

00:17:32.470 --> 00:17:33.850
I think he's right.

00:17:33.850 --> 00:17:38.830
It's not going to spread here,
because we have the ability

00:17:38.830 --> 00:17:42.590
to do what's needed, which is
isolate the infectious patient

00:17:42.590 --> 00:17:45.020
while actually
giving him good care,

00:17:45.020 --> 00:17:48.975
and then doing contact
tracing, which is, as he said,

00:17:48.975 --> 00:17:51.290
bread and butter
of public health.

00:17:51.290 --> 00:17:53.605
And to do it, it requires
a lot of resources.

00:17:55.974 --> 00:17:57.390
And that's the
right way to do it.

00:17:57.390 --> 00:18:02.700
And I think that would happen
in the European countries I've

00:18:02.700 --> 00:18:03.200
been to.

00:18:03.200 --> 00:18:04.470
It'll happen here.

00:18:04.470 --> 00:18:08.190
So I think we've got a very
good chance of seeing cases,

00:18:08.190 --> 00:18:13.122
but not of seeing much in the
way of person to person spread.

00:18:13.122 --> 00:18:14.080
I mean, it will happen.

00:18:14.080 --> 00:18:17.280
JACQUELINE FULLER: Unless
the virus mutates, and then--

00:18:18.917 --> 00:18:21.250
PAUL FARMER: Well, the virus
will mutate, I've no doubt.

00:18:21.250 --> 00:18:23.270
The question of whether
or not that will change

00:18:23.270 --> 00:18:25.105
is either its virulence
or transmissibility.

00:18:26.640 --> 00:18:28.960
Viruses and bugs--
they always mutate

00:18:28.960 --> 00:18:31.520
when we poke at them
with antibiotics

00:18:31.520 --> 00:18:34.384
or other-- so, parasites, too.

00:18:34.384 --> 00:18:35.300
JACQUELINE FULLER: OK.

00:18:35.300 --> 00:18:36.716
So then, thinking
about treatment,

00:18:36.716 --> 00:18:39.905
there's been an interesting
sort of debate, discussion,

00:18:39.905 --> 00:18:43.670
in some of the articles about
what's the best approach?

00:18:43.670 --> 00:18:45.960
And so you have,
say, [INAUDIBLE]

00:18:45.960 --> 00:18:49.980
on one hand advocating a very
patient centered focus, making

00:18:49.980 --> 00:18:52.350
sure we take absolute best
care and best standards.

00:18:53.790 --> 00:18:54.780
You have WHO.

00:18:56.380 --> 00:18:58.776
CDC's sort of more of a public
health mindset coming in,

00:18:58.776 --> 00:19:01.275
saying, well, we need to try
these community health centers.

00:19:03.450 --> 00:19:08.210
I mean, your thoughts
on if you were

00:19:08.210 --> 00:19:12.340
the czar in charge of
ebola, what would you do?

00:19:12.340 --> 00:19:14.770
PAUL FARMER: Well,
first of all, I

00:19:14.770 --> 00:19:17.820
think that, unfortunately,
no one is really

00:19:17.820 --> 00:19:20.510
advocating for a high
standard of care yet.

00:19:22.320 --> 00:19:26.860
That would require, for the
critically ill, critical care.

00:19:26.860 --> 00:19:27.850
There's this confusion.

00:19:27.850 --> 00:19:29.600
People think that
supportive care

00:19:29.600 --> 00:19:31.900
means holding someone's hand.

00:19:31.900 --> 00:19:34.062
And if you're in
hypovolemic shock,

00:19:34.062 --> 00:19:35.770
then you're just going
to hold their hand

00:19:35.770 --> 00:19:37.240
while they die unnecessarily.

00:19:38.450 --> 00:19:40.940
So I think we have
a long way to go

00:19:40.940 --> 00:19:45.150
before we can say that
there's any real progress

00:19:45.150 --> 00:19:46.990
on the quality of care.

00:19:46.990 --> 00:19:50.010
And again, that's not to
criticize any organization,

00:19:50.010 --> 00:19:55.260
especially any that shows up
early to try and save lives.

00:19:55.260 --> 00:20:00.270
But what it looks like a patient
focused versus public health--

00:20:00.270 --> 00:20:02.080
we're not even there
yet, because we've

00:20:02.080 --> 00:20:04.630
got neither going on.

00:20:04.630 --> 00:20:06.280
And both could go on.

00:20:06.280 --> 00:20:11.100
And the one thing I would
say early on in the epidemic

00:20:11.100 --> 00:20:17.050
is every time we've
tried to oppose treatment

00:20:17.050 --> 00:20:20.390
and prevention, we've failed.

00:20:20.390 --> 00:20:22.510
You integrate treatment
and prevention.

00:20:22.510 --> 00:20:26.230
So if you can't drag
people, pull people

00:20:26.230 --> 00:20:29.920
in to your care,
which involves what?

00:20:29.920 --> 00:20:31.110
Involves isolation.

00:20:31.110 --> 00:20:33.792
That word just means
following [INAUDIBLE] control.

00:20:34.970 --> 00:20:37.140
It sounds bad in lay
language, like supportive

00:20:37.140 --> 00:20:39.770
care sounds like
singing kumbaya.

00:20:39.770 --> 00:20:41.406
Please don't do that
if I'm in shock.

00:20:42.864 --> 00:20:44.170
Please don't do that anytime.

00:20:45.390 --> 00:20:47.185
I went to a Catholic
youth organization.

00:20:49.580 --> 00:20:53.550
So just as supportive care is
not singing kumbaya and holding

00:20:53.550 --> 00:20:58.940
hands, so, too, is isolation
just a technical term

00:20:58.940 --> 00:21:02.200
to prevent the infection
from reaching other people.

00:21:02.200 --> 00:21:04.050
And the best way to
do that is pull people

00:21:04.050 --> 00:21:06.000
in with good care
and good service.

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:06.230
JACQUELINE FULLER: Right.

00:21:06.230 --> 00:21:07.410
Giving them incentive
to go, like,

00:21:07.410 --> 00:21:09.500
we trust that the system's
going to care for them.

00:21:09.500 --> 00:21:10.375
PAUL FARMER: Exactly.

00:21:10.375 --> 00:21:16.510
And feed them, and let
them-- imagine being shut out

00:21:16.510 --> 00:21:18.360
of modern medicine forever.

00:21:18.360 --> 00:21:21.270
There's never been a collision
of ebola and modern medicine

00:21:21.270 --> 00:21:22.990
before that I know of.

00:21:22.990 --> 00:21:26.640
So then you have people showing
up in space suits or something,

00:21:26.640 --> 00:21:29.420
and then you don't
see your family again.

00:21:29.420 --> 00:21:34.160
And if that's going to
happen, which it should,

00:21:34.160 --> 00:21:37.870
it's got to be linked to a
warm welcome and survival.

00:21:37.870 --> 00:21:40.790
And that'll happen if we
have food and medical care,

00:21:40.790 --> 00:21:43.740
and there's a way to do it.

00:21:43.740 --> 00:21:47.690
And that's where we should
go and invest really heavily

00:21:47.690 --> 00:21:49.800
in improving the quality
of care and making sure

00:21:49.800 --> 00:21:52.310
our public health is stronger.

00:21:52.310 --> 00:21:55.720
In some countries that have been
credited with stopping ebola,

00:21:55.720 --> 00:21:59.020
it took, really, hundreds,
if not thousands,

00:21:59.020 --> 00:22:01.960
of staffers to do the contact
tracing-- community health

00:22:01.960 --> 00:22:03.200
workers, especially.

00:22:03.200 --> 00:22:05.760
And that's the way to go.

00:22:05.760 --> 00:22:07.630
So even though you're
right, everybody

00:22:07.630 --> 00:22:09.570
is saying a high
standard of care

00:22:09.570 --> 00:22:11.240
versus public
health, that's been

00:22:11.240 --> 00:22:13.510
a dead end with every other
epidemic I can think of.

00:22:15.270 --> 00:22:17.720
JACQUELINE FULLER: Well, you
mentioned contact tracing.

00:22:17.720 --> 00:22:21.000
One of the things that we
at Google have been thinking

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:23.960
about across many, many
teams is just what can we do?

00:22:23.960 --> 00:22:24.910
How can we be helpful?

00:22:24.910 --> 00:22:26.710
What can we do
that's differential?

00:22:26.710 --> 00:22:30.350
So google.org-- we've
invested about half a million

00:22:30.350 --> 00:22:33.960
to some groups like
[INAUDIBLE], UNICEF,

00:22:33.960 --> 00:22:38.220
others who are doing contract
tracing, thinking about how can

00:22:38.220 --> 00:22:40.440
we help with some of
the best mobile tools

00:22:40.440 --> 00:22:42.820
available out there to
help with epidemiology?

00:22:44.200 --> 00:22:47.110
We have our geo
team, for example,

00:22:47.110 --> 00:22:49.080
that's helping to
do things, even

00:22:49.080 --> 00:22:51.780
like providing
really accurate maps

00:22:51.780 --> 00:22:55.010
with roads and critical
information on them.

00:22:56.150 --> 00:22:58.260
We have a creative lab
group, for example,

00:22:58.260 --> 00:23:01.710
that normally works on general
marketing that's doing things

00:23:01.710 --> 00:23:05.980
like helping to create visual
images to do communication,

00:23:05.980 --> 00:23:09.044
so that people in low
literacy environments

00:23:09.044 --> 00:23:10.960
can understand how to
take care of themselves,

00:23:10.960 --> 00:23:14.121
how to take care of other
people, our crisis response

00:23:14.121 --> 00:23:14.620
team.

00:23:16.984 --> 00:23:18.650
This is happening in
regions, obviously,

00:23:18.650 --> 00:23:20.740
where internet
penetration is very low,

00:23:20.740 --> 00:23:23.540
so some of our typical
tools in our toolbox

00:23:23.540 --> 00:23:24.420
are not as effective.

00:23:26.220 --> 00:23:28.491
But we're looking at, can
we be helpful in terms

00:23:28.491 --> 00:23:29.990
of people searching
for information?

00:23:31.320 --> 00:23:33.280
One box is providing
information and hotlines.

00:23:34.930 --> 00:23:37.640
And Googlers, if you're
wondering what you can do,

00:23:37.640 --> 00:23:40.980
if you're in the room,
there's a badge set up

00:23:40.980 --> 00:23:44.140
in the back where you can go and
donate to Partners in Health,

00:23:44.140 --> 00:23:46.670
some other orgs on
the front lines.

00:23:46.670 --> 00:23:49.260
You can also join Ebola Announce
if you want more information

00:23:49.260 --> 00:23:51.170
about what's
happening at Google.

00:23:51.170 --> 00:23:53.504
But those are just
some of the areas

00:23:53.504 --> 00:23:55.920
where we're trying to think
about how can we help in a way

00:23:55.920 --> 00:23:57.250
that best uses our strengths?

00:23:57.250 --> 00:23:59.041
But I'll just turn the
question over to you

00:23:59.041 --> 00:24:01.100
and say, what should
Google be doing?

00:24:01.100 --> 00:24:03.380
What should the tech
industry be doing?

00:24:03.380 --> 00:24:06.550
What should Americans, what
should be the rich world

00:24:06.550 --> 00:24:08.080
be doing in general
to help here?

00:24:09.730 --> 00:24:13.330
Well, first of all, those sound
like just the kind of things

00:24:13.330 --> 00:24:14.870
that we need Google to be doing.

00:24:14.870 --> 00:24:17.280
I mean, there's
more, of course, it

00:24:17.280 --> 00:24:18.870
will not shock you that I think.

00:24:20.740 --> 00:24:23.320
And I'd just really like
to formally introduce

00:24:23.320 --> 00:24:29.210
my colleague, Doctor Dan
Kelly, who is-- well,

00:24:29.210 --> 00:24:32.710
at least he was, until
about a month ago,

00:24:32.710 --> 00:24:35.930
studying for infectious
disease physician

00:24:35.930 --> 00:24:38.600
training-- studying for an MPH.

00:24:38.600 --> 00:24:40.890
And he's been working in
Sierra Leone for some time.

00:24:40.890 --> 00:24:44.000
I said, well, time to
go back to Sierra Leone.

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:46.820
And we're actually
headed off together,

00:24:46.820 --> 00:24:51.450
along with our
colleagues, in a few days.

00:24:51.450 --> 00:24:54.700
So if you go out to the kind
of places where Well Body

00:24:54.700 --> 00:24:57.210
Alliance works, or
Last Mile Health,

00:24:57.210 --> 00:25:00.590
or Partners in Health's other
sister organization in Haiti

00:25:00.590 --> 00:25:03.650
that's [INAUDIBLE],
which many of you

00:25:03.650 --> 00:25:08.900
have supported after
the earthquake,

00:25:08.900 --> 00:25:11.600
a lot of the very
tools you mentioned

00:25:11.600 --> 00:25:14.630
have not been available
to the poor, right?

00:25:16.080 --> 00:25:18.366
It's worse in those
parts of Africa

00:25:18.366 --> 00:25:19.740
with internet
penetration than it

00:25:19.740 --> 00:25:24.260
is in Haiti, which
is bad enough.

00:25:25.280 --> 00:25:27.790
So we don't know
what's happening

00:25:27.790 --> 00:25:30.540
where cases are popping up, and
I've seen that already being

00:25:30.540 --> 00:25:33.770
useful-- those technologies
are already proving useful.

00:25:33.770 --> 00:25:36.210
And I would just
encourage you all

00:25:36.210 --> 00:25:41.060
to keep pushing these
out to the rural poor.

00:25:41.060 --> 00:25:46.070
The rural poor are the last ones
to benefit, in my experience,

00:25:46.070 --> 00:25:48.450
from technological advances.

00:25:48.450 --> 00:25:50.580
And, again, there's
no reason that

00:25:50.580 --> 00:25:53.300
has to be the same
next year as it

00:25:53.300 --> 00:25:55.940
was 50 years ago
or 10 years ago.

00:25:55.940 --> 00:25:59.680
So that last mile issue
of going to the people

00:25:59.680 --> 00:26:04.350
really shut out of modernity--
I think Google can push that,

00:26:04.350 --> 00:26:05.790
right?

00:26:05.790 --> 00:26:11.760
And another thing that I've
found very helpful for 30 years

00:26:11.760 --> 00:26:18.090
is this which we stole
from liberation theology--

00:26:18.090 --> 00:26:19.820
a preferential
option for the poor.

00:26:19.820 --> 00:26:22.720
It's kind of a simple
idea, but very radical.

00:26:23.760 --> 00:26:27.440
Say you're a doctor, and you can
say, I take care of everybody,

00:26:27.440 --> 00:26:31.160
but my primary concern is
people who are sick and poor.

00:26:31.160 --> 00:26:36.270
That kind of thinking too
rarely invades foundations,

00:26:36.270 --> 00:26:39.780
educational institutions,
universities, companies.

00:26:39.780 --> 00:26:41.800
And I'm only saying
it because I think

00:26:41.800 --> 00:26:45.070
it's really helpful, because
that's the big challenge.

00:26:45.070 --> 00:26:47.400
That's another
kind of last mile.

00:26:47.400 --> 00:26:51.360
A third is don't buy it
when people say, well, this

00:26:51.360 --> 00:26:53.640
is a really straightforward
intervention.

00:26:53.640 --> 00:26:55.630
It's all about-- and
then fill in the blank.

00:26:55.630 --> 00:26:57.800
It's all about prevention, it's
all about improving quality.

00:26:57.800 --> 00:26:59.549
It's not all about
either of those things.

00:26:59.549 --> 00:27:03.050
It's really going
to be hard, and it's

00:27:03.050 --> 00:27:05.100
going to require
the kind of tools

00:27:05.100 --> 00:27:08.360
that I think people here
would take for granted.

00:27:08.360 --> 00:27:10.960
Now, all that said,
the other thing

00:27:10.960 --> 00:27:12.430
is, please be patient with us.

00:27:12.430 --> 00:27:15.135
You are the ones who are the
Googlers and the engineers,

00:27:15.135 --> 00:27:16.220
not us.

00:27:16.220 --> 00:27:17.350
I'm a doctor.

00:27:18.570 --> 00:27:22.720
I don't expect you to understand
how to dose [INAUDIBLE]

00:27:22.720 --> 00:27:27.400
or to use the right
prophylaxis for malaria.

00:27:27.400 --> 00:27:29.530
I know that stuff, though.

00:27:29.530 --> 00:27:33.990
But we don't know from
engineering or from IT.

00:27:33.990 --> 00:27:36.820
Well, some people on our team
do, but not a lot of us, right?

00:27:36.820 --> 00:27:40.900
So we need you to be patient and
to accompany us with the gifts

00:27:40.900 --> 00:27:42.970
that you have over
the long term.

00:27:42.970 --> 00:27:49.750
I said this after the
earthquake in Haiti,

00:27:49.750 --> 00:27:52.370
and we did some of the things
that we said we would do.

00:27:52.370 --> 00:27:55.290
I'd like to think we did all
the things we said we would do.

00:27:55.290 --> 00:27:58.260
We did build that medical
center in central Haiti.

00:27:58.260 --> 00:28:01.560
We did make it the largest
solar powered hospital

00:28:01.560 --> 00:28:02.600
in the developing world.

00:28:02.600 --> 00:28:06.070
We did build a new IT backbone
to connect it to the Harvard

00:28:06.070 --> 00:28:10.930
teaching hospitals so that
you can see an x-ray in Boston

00:28:10.930 --> 00:28:14.080
at the same time that you
see it in central Haiti.

00:28:14.080 --> 00:28:17.980
We did put a CAT scan-- the
first one in a public hospital

00:28:17.980 --> 00:28:20.460
anywhere in Haiti--
in rural Haiti,

00:28:20.460 --> 00:28:23.610
and, again, connected it to
whatever it goes through.

00:28:23.610 --> 00:28:25.187
God or Google or whatever.

00:28:27.129 --> 00:28:28.920
JACQUELINE FULLER:
We'll go with the cloud.

00:28:28.920 --> 00:28:31.250
PAUL FARMER: That
accompaniment is critical.

00:28:31.250 --> 00:28:33.550
We're begging, be
patient with us.

00:28:33.550 --> 00:28:37.410
You know things we don't
know, and we really need that.

00:28:37.410 --> 00:28:43.160
And then third,
this kind of work

00:28:43.160 --> 00:28:48.360
needs resources that
can be turned on a dime.

00:28:48.360 --> 00:28:51.489
Why do you think all
these huge bureaucracies--

00:28:51.489 --> 00:28:52.780
they've been there a long time.

00:28:54.110 --> 00:28:57.400
The UN very humbly,
when I was there,

00:28:57.400 --> 00:28:59.890
they were doing our
transport in Liberia,

00:28:59.890 --> 00:29:02.990
because there's no
air bridge, right?

00:29:04.050 --> 00:29:06.020
The airlines aren't
flying, really.

00:29:06.020 --> 00:29:08.040
And it'll be worse
now that you've

00:29:08.040 --> 00:29:09.670
had a commercial carrier.

00:29:09.670 --> 00:29:15.040
I actually flew out, I just
noticed, on the same day

00:29:15.040 --> 00:29:16.790
as that patient, or
the day before, right?

00:29:18.220 --> 00:29:20.940
So I haven't finished
my 21 days either.

00:29:20.940 --> 00:29:22.700
JACQUELINE FULLER: Good to know.

00:29:22.700 --> 00:29:24.330
PAUL FARMER: If
anyone gave me a hug.

00:29:24.330 --> 00:29:26.990
But it's going to
make it worse, right?

00:29:26.990 --> 00:29:31.620
So the UN was very grateful
that they got us around,

00:29:31.620 --> 00:29:33.120
including in the rural areas.

00:29:33.120 --> 00:29:36.420
But they were saying, hey, we
worked on this for 10 years,

00:29:36.420 --> 00:29:39.680
and then one epidemic,
and everything fell over.

00:29:39.680 --> 00:29:42.010
And that's the right
humility, I think.

00:29:42.010 --> 00:29:44.270
Not everybody would
say that, but they did.

00:29:44.270 --> 00:29:49.980
So one of the problems is that
if you study bureaucracy like

00:29:49.980 --> 00:29:52.690
the sociologist Max Weber--
see, aren't you scared that

00:29:52.690 --> 00:29:54.075
I'm going off with some--

00:29:54.075 --> 00:29:54.570
JACQUELINE FULLER: Yeah.

00:29:54.570 --> 00:29:55.070
Questions?

00:29:55.070 --> 00:29:55.778
No, just kidding.

00:29:57.000 --> 00:29:58.990
PAUL FARMER: OK, I won't
quote sociologists.

00:30:00.050 --> 00:30:03.940
But that flexibility--
that only comes

00:30:03.940 --> 00:30:05.620
from discretionary capital.

00:30:05.620 --> 00:30:06.920
You guys know that in business.

00:30:06.920 --> 00:30:08.100
You can't not know that.

00:30:08.100 --> 00:30:08.390
We need that.

00:30:08.390 --> 00:30:09.030
JACQUELINE FULLER:
On the subject

00:30:09.030 --> 00:30:10.830
of discretionary
capital and what

00:30:10.830 --> 00:30:13.314
we can do-- I mean,
on your site--

00:30:13.314 --> 00:30:15.730
and this is something that we
pushed when we were at Gates

00:30:15.730 --> 00:30:20.210
Foundation before Google is if
you ask Americans how much do

00:30:20.210 --> 00:30:23.430
you think that we spend
on humanitarian aid,

00:30:23.430 --> 00:30:25.130
the average guess is about 10%.

00:30:26.230 --> 00:30:29.150
And in reality, we
spend less than 1%

00:30:29.150 --> 00:30:31.200
of our budget on
humanitarian aid.

00:30:31.200 --> 00:30:36.410
So just sort of taking a wider
view, now, from ebola, just

00:30:36.410 --> 00:30:40.410
on global health in general,
global development in general,

00:30:40.410 --> 00:30:44.180
it seems like we're going to
lurch from epidemic to epidemic

00:30:44.180 --> 00:30:46.740
to crises to crises
until we spend

00:30:46.740 --> 00:30:49.020
some real resources in
some real smart ways.

00:30:49.020 --> 00:30:52.420
PAUL FARMER: You know, I
heard Jim Kim said something

00:30:52.420 --> 00:30:53.999
really remarkable the other day.

00:30:53.999 --> 00:30:56.040
Well, I've been hearing
him say remarkable things

00:30:56.040 --> 00:30:57.570
for a long time.

00:30:57.570 --> 00:31:03.810
But he said that he spends a lot
of his time talking people out

00:31:03.810 --> 00:31:07.630
of talking themselves out
of doing the right thing.

00:31:07.630 --> 00:31:13.410
And that's because we're all so
socialized for scarcity, right?

00:31:13.410 --> 00:31:21.950
And that's a bad thing,
because we can romanticize

00:31:21.950 --> 00:31:26.570
frugal innovation,
but I don't buy it.

00:31:26.570 --> 00:31:28.900
Sitting in the middle
of a squatter settlement

00:31:28.900 --> 00:31:34.077
in Haiti, or in a rain forest
with no electricity-- that

00:31:34.077 --> 00:31:35.660
is a dangerous kind
of romanticization

00:31:35.660 --> 00:31:37.730
in the middle of an epidemic.

00:31:37.730 --> 00:31:41.520
And so I know it
sounds attractive,

00:31:41.520 --> 00:31:43.900
but we've got to
have, like you said,

00:31:43.900 --> 00:31:46.390
more resources put
into these problems.

00:31:46.390 --> 00:31:53.030
I mean, none of us, if
we were critically ill,

00:31:53.030 --> 00:31:56.850
would not want to have care,
nor would we want our kids

00:31:56.850 --> 00:32:02.020
to settle for or
get second best.

00:32:02.020 --> 00:32:05.570
That's how most of the people
I see in a clinic or hospital

00:32:05.570 --> 00:32:06.222
feel as well.

00:32:06.222 --> 00:32:07.430
JACQUELINE FULLER: All right.

00:32:07.430 --> 00:32:09.910
So we're going to turn
to live questions now,

00:32:09.910 --> 00:32:11.660
and we have a mic right
there in the back.

00:32:11.660 --> 00:32:13.620
And then we'll also
take some from the Dory.

00:32:13.620 --> 00:32:15.730
Can we get the
Dory questions up?

00:32:15.730 --> 00:32:16.230
Great.

00:32:16.230 --> 00:32:19.460
So while people are working
their way to the microphone,

00:32:19.460 --> 00:32:21.500
what's your message
to the average

00:32:21.500 --> 00:32:24.810
citizen in the empowered
world, in the developed world,

00:32:24.810 --> 00:32:26.820
on what can I do?

00:32:26.820 --> 00:32:28.650
What can an average citizen do?

00:32:31.530 --> 00:32:35.410
PAUL FARMER: Well,
I think it's better

00:32:35.410 --> 00:32:39.990
to imagine that there's
something you can do, even

00:32:39.990 --> 00:32:43.572
to respond to a
problem that seems so

00:32:43.572 --> 00:32:44.905
remote from your own experience.

00:32:46.880 --> 00:32:56.020
And whether you call that
empathy or-- it's not

00:32:56.020 --> 00:32:58.079
like pity or mercy are
bad, either, right?

00:32:58.079 --> 00:32:59.120
Those are not bad things.

00:32:59.120 --> 00:32:59.870
JACQUELINE FULLER:
We'll take them.

00:32:59.870 --> 00:32:59.930
PAUL FARMER: Yeah.

00:32:59.930 --> 00:33:00.430
We'll take them.

00:33:00.430 --> 00:33:01.490
JACQUELINE FULLER: If I'm
dying in that rainforest,

00:33:01.490 --> 00:33:02.369
I'll take it.

00:33:02.369 --> 00:33:03.660
PAUL FARMER: Exactly, you know?

00:33:03.660 --> 00:33:06.330
And we should remember that.

00:33:06.330 --> 00:33:09.210
Mercy is a good thing.

00:33:09.210 --> 00:33:13.510
In fact, back to my
PTSD Catholic youth,

00:33:13.510 --> 00:33:15.220
it's one of the
cardinal virtues.

00:33:15.220 --> 00:33:16.220
JACQUELINE FULLER: Yeah.

00:33:17.090 --> 00:33:19.340
PAUL FARMER: On the other
hand, if you could link that

00:33:19.340 --> 00:33:24.550
to solidarity, and then
link that to pragmatics,

00:33:24.550 --> 00:33:28.630
that'll really help with a
problem like this, right?

00:33:28.630 --> 00:33:35.430
So in addition to watching
wherever it is you're watching,

00:33:35.430 --> 00:33:39.170
or thinking or listening or
hearing about a problem that

00:33:39.170 --> 00:33:43.060
seems remote, I think
right now, what that region

00:33:43.060 --> 00:33:45.810
needs most of all is some of
that pragmatic solidarity.

00:33:47.400 --> 00:33:51.860
And they need
help-- material help

00:33:51.860 --> 00:33:55.010
with rebuilding a health system
that could be more robust.

00:33:57.430 --> 00:34:01.080
After all, these
are all areas driven

00:34:01.080 --> 00:34:05.220
by conflict in recent
times, and those

00:34:05.220 --> 00:34:07.525
are transnational conflicts.

00:34:07.525 --> 00:34:09.409
It's not like something
that happened just

00:34:09.409 --> 00:34:12.239
in Liberia or just
in Sierra Leone.

00:34:12.239 --> 00:34:14.260
This is not like
blood diamonds--

00:34:14.260 --> 00:34:16.540
like they're wearing them
on their hands, right?

00:34:17.929 --> 00:34:20.960
So thinking about
that pragmatic piece,

00:34:20.960 --> 00:34:26.380
and then link that
to organizations

00:34:26.380 --> 00:34:27.678
that you have faith in.

00:34:27.678 --> 00:34:29.469
JACQUELINE FULLER: Like
Partners in Health.

00:34:29.469 --> 00:34:30.320
PAUL FARMER: Like
Partners in Health.

00:34:30.320 --> 00:34:31.770
I mean, we're proud
to be part of that.

00:34:31.770 --> 00:34:32.889
JACQUELINE FULLER:
Badge donate in back.

00:34:32.889 --> 00:34:35.347
PAUL FARMER: I'll just give
you an example-- something that

00:34:35.347 --> 00:34:40.110
gave me chill bumps
and moved me very much.

00:34:40.110 --> 00:34:47.300
An American actor named
Jeffrey Wright got it

00:34:47.300 --> 00:34:48.780
that there's
something wrong here,

00:34:48.780 --> 00:34:51.889
that we can't give up on
people and think they're all

00:34:51.889 --> 00:34:53.454
going to die when
they have ebola.

00:34:54.780 --> 00:34:57.042
And exactly what
every doctor and nurse

00:34:57.042 --> 00:34:58.250
should have said, by the way.

00:34:58.250 --> 00:34:59.625
Wait, you're
telling me that it's

00:34:59.625 --> 00:35:02.480
because they have
hypovolemic shock?

00:35:04.020 --> 00:35:05.520
JACQUELINE FULLER:
That's treatable.

00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:06.800
PAUL FARMER: And
that's treatable.

00:35:06.800 --> 00:35:08.155
Or they're losing electrolytes.

00:35:09.980 --> 00:35:16.010
And so he started a
public service campaign

00:35:16.010 --> 00:35:20.740
about survival, and
to get the message out

00:35:20.740 --> 00:35:23.860
that we've got to fight
for people to survive.

00:35:23.860 --> 00:35:26.665
Don't forget, when people
survive, they become immune.

00:35:28.280 --> 00:35:29.662
That's what it looks like to us.

00:35:29.662 --> 00:35:31.037
JACQUELINE FULLER:
And gives hope

00:35:31.037 --> 00:35:32.695
to everyone else observing them.

00:35:32.695 --> 00:35:34.820
PAUL FARMER: That they can
be part of the solution.

00:35:34.820 --> 00:35:37.070
JACQUELINE FULLER: That I
don't need to hide this.

00:35:37.070 --> 00:35:38.700
I can come forward.

00:35:38.700 --> 00:35:41.990
PAUL FARMER: And they
can help us in our work.

00:35:41.990 --> 00:35:42.635
I'm not immune.

00:35:44.580 --> 00:35:45.855
They are.

00:35:45.855 --> 00:35:47.980
Now, not everybody's going
to want to work on that,

00:35:47.980 --> 00:35:49.720
but that's just an example.

00:35:49.720 --> 00:35:53.520
People think, OK, there's
somebody who's survived ebola.

00:35:53.520 --> 00:35:55.550
What if they're part
of the solution?

00:35:55.550 --> 00:35:57.880
That's what happened
with AIDS activism.

00:35:57.880 --> 00:35:59.970
Let's have ebola activism.

00:35:59.970 --> 00:36:05.615
Let's make sure that there's
a place for them to help.

00:36:05.615 --> 00:36:08.910
And I know it sounds
kind of corny,

00:36:08.910 --> 00:36:12.430
but I feel that way about
everybody about global health

00:36:12.430 --> 00:36:14.280
equity is that everybody
can help somehow.

00:36:14.280 --> 00:36:15.821
JACQUELINE FULLER:
And I think that's

00:36:15.821 --> 00:36:17.850
part of the magic that
ignited the generation is

00:36:17.850 --> 00:36:20.630
that every person
matters, and that we

00:36:20.630 --> 00:36:22.910
need to do we can
do to save everyone,

00:36:22.910 --> 00:36:24.000
because each life matters.

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:25.360
So first question.

00:36:25.360 --> 00:36:27.520
I see Raquel, who's an
engineer with google.org,

00:36:27.520 --> 00:36:30.890
and has helped leading our
crisis response on this.

00:36:32.107 --> 00:36:34.690
AUDIENCE: You said there's not
enough T in the ebola treatment

00:36:34.690 --> 00:36:36.290
units, and that
we haven't really

00:36:36.290 --> 00:36:39.570
reached the highest
quality of care possible.

00:36:39.570 --> 00:36:45.730
So what I want to understand
is if there aren't enough

00:36:45.730 --> 00:36:49.330
actual physical doctors, enough
actual beds, enough capacity

00:36:49.330 --> 00:36:50.515
in the treatment centers?

00:36:50.515 --> 00:36:51.890
Because in a lot
of conversations

00:36:51.890 --> 00:36:54.530
we've had with various
people, all sorts

00:36:54.530 --> 00:36:56.470
of health
organizations who we've

00:36:56.470 --> 00:36:58.595
been talking with to
see how Google can help,

00:36:58.595 --> 00:37:00.970
one thing that we've heard--
and maybe this has changed--

00:37:00.970 --> 00:37:02.770
is, well, we don't need money.

00:37:02.770 --> 00:37:04.197
We need leadership
and direction.

00:37:04.197 --> 00:37:06.530
And maybe this is more around
some of the tech solutions

00:37:06.530 --> 00:37:08.150
we were talking
about, but the sense

00:37:08.150 --> 00:37:11.299
that the money's
flowing in, but we

00:37:11.299 --> 00:37:13.590
need people who know how to
execute, organize, connect,

00:37:13.590 --> 00:37:14.860
deploy, train.

00:37:14.860 --> 00:37:15.630
All these things.

00:37:15.630 --> 00:37:18.280
It's people.

00:37:20.350 --> 00:37:22.950
But it seems like that may not
be the case, if it's really

00:37:22.950 --> 00:37:26.475
that we don't have
enough actual physicians.

00:37:27.660 --> 00:37:30.360
PAUL FARMER: Well, I
don't think that it's true

00:37:30.360 --> 00:37:31.970
that we have enough money.

00:37:31.970 --> 00:37:34.030
First of all, a pledge
is not the same,

00:37:34.030 --> 00:37:36.480
as you know, as delivery.

00:37:36.480 --> 00:37:39.770
That's just the
beginning of a process

00:37:39.770 --> 00:37:41.890
to get to the last mile.

00:37:41.890 --> 00:37:47.120
So again, I would say
that is incorrect.

00:37:47.120 --> 00:37:47.960
I've heard it, too.

00:37:47.960 --> 00:37:49.240
It's just not true.

00:37:49.240 --> 00:37:53.590
We need massive resources
and a commitment to delivery.

00:37:53.590 --> 00:37:54.580
We've studied this now.

00:37:54.580 --> 00:37:57.705
In fact, we've used
IT platforms just

00:37:57.705 --> 00:38:01.180
to ask a simple question
after the Asian earthquake.

00:38:01.180 --> 00:38:03.770
How many of these pledges
are actually delivered?

00:38:03.770 --> 00:38:06.910
And that's just delivered
to a place where

00:38:06.910 --> 00:38:08.410
they could be
delivered as services.

00:38:08.410 --> 00:38:10.618
JACQUELINE FULLER: How of
it actually hits the field?

00:38:10.618 --> 00:38:13.230
PAUL FARMER: And that's just a
national capital kind of thing.

00:38:13.230 --> 00:38:15.720
We found out the answer
is not very attractive.

00:38:17.840 --> 00:38:25.080
So we basically need staff,
stuff, space, and systems.

00:38:25.080 --> 00:38:26.185
We don't have any of them.

00:38:26.185 --> 00:38:27.120
JACQUELINE FULLER:
What's the hashtag?

00:38:27.120 --> 00:38:28.036
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:38:29.142 --> 00:38:29.975
