00:38:57.371 --> 00:39:03.690
PAUL FARMER: Well, I think we're
counting on your discernment

00:39:03.690 --> 00:39:08.110
and everybody's
discernment, because first

00:39:08.110 --> 00:39:09.925
of all, most of
that critical care

00:39:09.925 --> 00:39:12.540
is delivered by
nurses, not doctors.

00:39:13.630 --> 00:39:17.810
Go into the emergency room, the
urgent care center-- someone

00:39:17.810 --> 00:39:18.550
needs an IV.

00:39:20.510 --> 00:39:21.155
It's nurses.

00:39:22.270 --> 00:39:26.100
And I think if you go in to
your nurse or a physician--

00:39:26.100 --> 00:39:29.240
you go into an ETU
and you don't see

00:39:29.240 --> 00:39:31.840
this happening for
all kinds of reasons.

00:39:31.840 --> 00:39:35.100
But the reason isn't
that it isn't needed.

00:39:35.100 --> 00:39:40.530
Then, you know, we've got
to be tougher on ourselves,

00:39:40.530 --> 00:39:44.340
at least on the clinical side,
and say there's not enough.

00:39:44.340 --> 00:39:46.620
Again, if it were
you, I wouldn't

00:39:46.620 --> 00:39:48.167
want you to have
that kind of care.

00:39:48.167 --> 00:39:50.500
If it were me, I wouldn't
want to have that kind of care

00:39:50.500 --> 00:39:51.850
if I'm critically ill.

00:39:51.850 --> 00:39:53.530
If I've got a
hemorrhagic complication

00:39:53.530 --> 00:39:55.410
and a blood product
will help me,

00:39:55.410 --> 00:39:58.630
don't say it's
impossible to give blood.

00:39:58.630 --> 00:40:00.750
Let's say, instead,
we've got a long way

00:40:00.750 --> 00:40:04.700
to go on staff, stuff,
space, and systems.

00:40:04.700 --> 00:40:06.450
JACQUELINE FULLER: And
Partners in Health,

00:40:06.450 --> 00:40:07.908
along with a lot
of other orgs, are

00:40:07.908 --> 00:40:11.410
the ones who blew up
in this whole idea

00:40:11.410 --> 00:40:15.080
when people said we can't treat
AIDS in a place like Africa.

00:40:15.080 --> 00:40:16.280
We can't treat TB.

00:40:16.280 --> 00:40:18.570
We can't treat
multi-drug resistant TB.

00:40:18.570 --> 00:40:22.010
Partners in Health has proved
that we can do it, and do it

00:40:22.010 --> 00:40:24.370
in a very resource
effective way.

00:40:24.370 --> 00:40:25.400
Takes the mentality.

00:40:25.400 --> 00:40:26.640
PAUL FARMER: Yeah.

00:40:26.640 --> 00:40:28.440
And I think it takes
a different kind

00:40:28.440 --> 00:40:32.000
of idea, again, of
who the team is.

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:35.264
It's the community health
workers, but also the doctors.

00:40:35.264 --> 00:40:37.430
And if you go right through
that list-- don't worry,

00:40:37.430 --> 00:40:40.320
I won't-- staff,
stuff, space, systems--

00:40:40.320 --> 00:40:42.460
same things around AIDS.

00:40:42.460 --> 00:40:44.211
And again, just setting
our sights higher.

00:40:44.211 --> 00:40:46.460
JACQUELINE FULLER: All right,
we got another question.

00:40:46.460 --> 00:40:47.060
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:40:47.060 --> 00:40:49.143
I was just wondering if
you'd go a little bit more

00:40:49.143 --> 00:40:51.380
into what you think the
sociological angle of health

00:40:51.380 --> 00:40:52.940
care in West Africa
is, and how you

00:40:52.940 --> 00:40:54.685
think Weber work
applies to that.

00:40:54.685 --> 00:40:56.060
JACQUELINE FULLER:
Did you really

00:40:56.060 --> 00:40:57.190
ask him to quote [INAUDIBLE]?

00:40:57.190 --> 00:40:57.600
PAUL FARMER: He did.

00:40:57.600 --> 00:40:58.490
I'm so happy.

00:40:58.490 --> 00:41:01.895
I've been waiting for this
since Google was founded.

00:41:03.030 --> 00:41:07.110
So Max Weber was this great
sociologist 100 years ago

00:41:07.110 --> 00:41:11.270
who wrote some classics
like "On Bureaucracy," which

00:41:11.270 --> 00:41:13.730
I use in teaching global health.

00:41:13.730 --> 00:41:16.360
Because-- and I'll just say
the short version, concision

00:41:16.360 --> 00:41:20.280
not being my strong suit--
that his predictions

00:41:20.280 --> 00:41:24.090
about bureaucracy,
policy, moving away

00:41:24.090 --> 00:41:26.640
from charismatic authority
to bureaucracies,

00:41:26.640 --> 00:41:28.254
all have come true.

00:41:28.254 --> 00:41:29.920
And the only reason
to keep that in mind

00:41:29.920 --> 00:41:35.822
is that every time you fix
as policy a standard, what

00:41:35.822 --> 00:41:37.450
if something new comes along?

00:41:37.450 --> 00:41:38.310
It's like a budget.

00:41:38.310 --> 00:41:41.170
You say, well, ebola's
not in our budget.

00:41:41.170 --> 00:41:42.920
Well, that means that
your budget's wrong,

00:41:42.920 --> 00:41:45.210
not that the virus is wrong.

00:41:45.210 --> 00:41:49.410
And sociologically or
whatever, politically, this

00:41:49.410 --> 00:41:51.260
is what happens all the time.

00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:55.690
This is why you get big
moral errors like, well,

00:41:55.690 --> 00:41:58.060
we don't treat AIDS in Africa.

00:41:59.400 --> 00:42:01.830
And it's absurd.

00:42:01.830 --> 00:42:03.530
And it happens every time.

00:42:03.530 --> 00:42:06.170
And then you have
to fight like hell

00:42:06.170 --> 00:42:09.070
to say, OK, what's the
global health equity agenda?

00:42:09.070 --> 00:42:12.395
Forget about the
plan that we had.

00:42:13.630 --> 00:42:16.152
If it didn't have cholera in
it, and cholera smacks Haiti,

00:42:16.152 --> 00:42:17.360
you'd better change the plan.

00:42:17.360 --> 00:42:18.750
You'd better change the budget.

00:42:18.750 --> 00:42:21.350
And that, again,
is difficult when

00:42:21.350 --> 00:42:23.780
you're socialized for scarcity,
and everything is about,

00:42:23.780 --> 00:42:25.150
well, let's do more for less.

00:42:27.520 --> 00:42:30.790
Look at the budgets
of those countries

00:42:30.790 --> 00:42:34.690
from the public
sector into help.

00:42:34.690 --> 00:42:37.740
They're at India
level per capita,

00:42:37.740 --> 00:42:39.110
which is very, very low.

00:42:39.110 --> 00:42:40.580
China's up here.

00:42:40.580 --> 00:42:43.820
Rwanda's above China per capita.

00:42:43.820 --> 00:42:45.830
That's why Rwanda has
such a strong health

00:42:45.830 --> 00:42:48.190
system is because
they invested in it,

00:42:48.190 --> 00:42:52.710
and they brought partners
in to invest in their plan,

00:42:52.710 --> 00:42:55.460
and they have to be
able to change it,

00:42:55.460 --> 00:42:57.110
like I said, on a dime.

00:42:57.110 --> 00:42:58.630
And that's hard.

00:42:58.630 --> 00:43:00.300
That's where I
imagine we're stuck

00:43:00.300 --> 00:43:02.401
in that part of the world.

00:43:02.401 --> 00:43:04.400
AUDIENCE: Do you have a
book you could recommend

00:43:04.400 --> 00:43:06.040
