00:43:15.700 --> 00:43:16.949
whether Weber or other people.

00:43:18.390 --> 00:43:19.765
PAUL FARMER: Meet
me after class.

00:43:20.870 --> 00:43:21.701
Yeah, I do.

00:43:21.701 --> 00:43:22.200
I do.

00:43:22.200 --> 00:43:23.770
I'll write some down for you.

00:43:23.770 --> 00:43:25.380
JACQUELINE FULLER: And we'll
publish it on Go Paul Farmer,

00:43:25.380 --> 00:43:27.010
so people can have
access to it, too.

00:43:27.010 --> 00:43:28.820
So why don't I take
a Dory question

00:43:28.820 --> 00:43:30.660
from one of our other offices?

00:43:31.402 --> 00:43:32.860
So what do you
think tech companies

00:43:32.860 --> 00:43:36.240
like Google can do to aid the
efforts in building a better,

00:43:36.240 --> 00:43:39.160
long lasting health
system in Africa?

00:43:39.160 --> 00:43:41.400
PAUL FARMER: Well, again,
this issue of-- hi, Dory.

00:43:44.630 --> 00:43:46.344
I wonder where they are.

00:43:46.344 --> 00:43:48.260
JACQUELINE FULLER: Who's
asking that question?

00:43:49.357 --> 00:43:50.440
PAUL FARMER: Can you tell?

00:43:52.430 --> 00:43:53.020
Ulan Bator.

00:43:55.146 --> 00:43:57.599
You know, it doesn't matter.

00:43:57.599 --> 00:43:58.390
I was just curious.

00:44:00.570 --> 00:44:04.950
I think one of the
things that you could do

00:44:04.950 --> 00:44:07.570
is, again, this
accompaniment idea.

00:44:07.570 --> 00:44:10.090
Because if you look at
the way that business

00:44:10.090 --> 00:44:13.120
is done contractually,
contractors,

00:44:13.120 --> 00:44:17.080
a beginning, and an end,
that's not what we need,

00:44:17.080 --> 00:44:17.750
I don't think.

00:44:17.750 --> 00:44:19.416
We need a long term
accompaniment model.

00:44:20.370 --> 00:44:24.424
Because it takes a long
time to build systems.

00:44:24.424 --> 00:44:26.340
You could say, well,
we're not in the business

00:44:26.340 --> 00:44:27.990
of building systems,
but you are.

00:44:27.990 --> 00:44:30.120
That's what Google does, right?

00:44:30.120 --> 00:44:32.130
And you do this in
settings where there's

00:44:32.130 --> 00:44:34.340
extreme poverty,
no electrical grid.

00:44:36.190 --> 00:44:39.160
People tend to have their--
and this is true, again,

00:44:39.160 --> 00:44:39.790
of all of us.

00:44:39.790 --> 00:44:40.880
Remember what Jim said.

00:44:40.880 --> 00:44:43.055
You spend a lot of time
trying to talk people out

00:44:43.055 --> 00:44:46.935
of talking themselves out
of doing the right thing.

00:44:46.935 --> 00:44:50.870
Accompaniment is
a balm-- B-A-L-M--

00:44:50.870 --> 00:44:53.860
for us from companies.

00:44:53.860 --> 00:44:59.870
And we just haven't had that
many experiences with companies

00:44:59.870 --> 00:45:03.080
or with foundations, sometimes.

00:45:03.080 --> 00:45:06.050
And we need more,
because that's the kind

00:45:06.050 --> 00:45:09.434
of fruitful relationship we
would seek with a tech company.

00:45:09.434 --> 00:45:10.350
JACQUELINE FULLER: OK.

00:45:10.350 --> 00:45:12.339
