live question.

00:45:12.339 --> 00:45:12.880
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:45:14.164 --> 00:45:16.580
Correct me if I'm wrong, because
I'm not a medical doctor,

00:45:16.580 --> 00:45:18.371
but a lot of the initial
symptoms for ebola

00:45:18.371 --> 00:45:21.430
are similar to the common
flu's initial symptoms.

00:45:21.430 --> 00:45:23.660
Do you think the media
possibly drumming up

00:45:23.660 --> 00:45:25.420
an ebola scare being
in the United States

00:45:25.420 --> 00:45:28.370
could overwhelm the US
health system to a point

00:45:28.370 --> 00:45:30.370
where the few ebola
cases possibly

00:45:30.370 --> 00:45:32.540
get overlooked with
too many people

00:45:32.540 --> 00:45:34.905
thinking they have ebola
when they just have the flu?

00:45:38.470 --> 00:45:40.740
PAUL FARMER: That's
a possibility,

00:45:40.740 --> 00:45:42.450
and it happens
every time there's

00:45:42.450 --> 00:45:45.480
a big scare of one
reason or another, right?

00:45:47.130 --> 00:45:50.940
I do think that with
better diagnostics-- let

00:45:50.940 --> 00:45:52.500
me just put it this way.

00:45:52.500 --> 00:45:56.540
I bet you everybody who's
working in an emergency room

00:45:56.540 --> 00:46:00.630
or urgent care center is
thinking ebola all the time

00:46:00.630 --> 00:46:02.140
now, right?

00:46:02.140 --> 00:46:07.190
And the day after the Texas
case, the next morning,

00:46:07.190 --> 00:46:11.250
I was teaching in an
infectious disease course,

00:46:11.250 --> 00:46:14.695
and I laid out a
typical presentation.

00:46:15.854 --> 00:46:17.520
And it would've been
malaria or typhoid,

00:46:17.520 --> 00:46:20.030
and half the room went, ebola.

00:46:20.030 --> 00:46:21.590
It was ebola, actually.

00:46:23.006 --> 00:46:31.307
So I think having a
heightened suspicion,

00:46:31.307 --> 00:46:33.390
as long you're not forgetting
the other, much more

00:46:33.390 --> 00:46:35.430
common and treatable
causes, I think

00:46:35.430 --> 00:46:36.920
it's probably a good thing.

00:46:36.920 --> 00:46:41.900
And we need better
diagnostics, but right now, I

00:46:41.900 --> 00:46:44.750
don't think it's a
bad thing to have

00:46:44.750 --> 00:46:48.730
this ridiculously heightened
sense that what if it's

00:46:48.730 --> 00:46:52.680
ebola, as long as we
know where ebola sits

00:46:52.680 --> 00:46:57.240
in the burden of disease that
could cause a fever, weakness,

00:46:57.240 --> 00:46:58.120
nausea, and vomiting.

00:46:58.120 --> 00:47:01.720
It's extremely low, for
sure, in the United States.

00:47:01.720 --> 00:47:05.540
And even in a place like
some parts of rural Guinea

00:47:05.540 --> 00:47:10.020
or Liberia, it would
still be extremely low.

00:47:10.020 --> 00:47:12.360
It would be much more
likely to be malaria.

00:47:13.810 --> 00:47:16.420
But it's good for everybody
to be worried about it.

00:47:16.420 --> 00:47:20.010
The problem is, as
Jackie pointed out,

00:47:20.010 --> 00:47:25.200
is now that the primary health
care system has tottered

00:47:25.200 --> 00:47:28.990
and fallen, getting it back
up again is going to require

00:47:28.990 --> 00:47:31.320
linking that anxiety
about one problem

00:47:31.320 --> 00:47:34.810
to linking that anxiety to all
the problems that are common.

