the levels they operate in?

00:50:16.080 --> 00:50:18.020
PAUL FARMER: Well,
I think it's better

00:50:18.020 --> 00:50:21.640
to assume that their
motivation is something good,

00:50:21.640 --> 00:50:24.365
and then entrap them
into decency, right?

00:50:28.590 --> 00:50:29.460
You feel me?

00:50:30.955 --> 00:50:32.160
I'm serious.

00:50:32.160 --> 00:50:39.140
I think to approach leaders
with a hermeneutic of suspicion

00:50:39.140 --> 00:50:43.920
and not engage them in a chance
to do something decent is bad

00:50:43.920 --> 00:50:48.690
for people marginalized by
poverty and racism and gender

00:50:48.690 --> 00:50:49.540
inequality, right?

00:50:50.670 --> 00:50:51.860
Don't do that.

00:50:51.860 --> 00:50:53.800
We shouldn't do that
on their behalfs,

00:50:53.800 --> 00:50:58.750
to say it's not worth working
with so and so world leader.

00:50:58.750 --> 00:51:03.290
The upstream downstream
is another one

00:51:03.290 --> 00:51:05.310
of those classic lessons, right?

00:51:05.310 --> 00:51:07.619
Where there's a sort
of Luddite approach

00:51:07.619 --> 00:51:09.410
to upstream downstream,
where we're saying,

00:51:09.410 --> 00:51:13.970
well, the upstream
determinants are all important,

00:51:13.970 --> 00:51:16.900
but if you're already
downstream-- if you already

00:51:16.900 --> 00:51:20.590
have ebola-- like I'm
saying, I want someone

00:51:20.590 --> 00:51:21.940
to be looking out for me.

00:51:21.940 --> 00:51:27.010
And I was just saying, I
was at Stanford saying,

00:51:27.010 --> 00:51:29.742
oh, I was stupid enough
to walk in front of a car

00:51:29.742 --> 00:51:30.950
when I was a medical student.

00:51:32.100 --> 00:51:34.340
And I didn't have my
M.D., and I looked

00:51:34.340 --> 00:51:38.110
at my leg lying in the street
and thought, hey, broken leg.

00:51:38.110 --> 00:51:40.385
I didn't even have my M.D.
What a great diagnostician.

00:51:42.030 --> 00:51:44.709
If someone had come over to
me, leaned over me, and said,

00:51:44.709 --> 00:51:46.250
hey, you should have
looked both ways

00:51:46.250 --> 00:51:49.930
before you cross the street--
if an ambulance attendant did

00:51:49.930 --> 00:51:53.750
that, I would be
really unhappy, right?

00:51:54.830 --> 00:51:57.190
That's what we do to
poor people all the time.

00:51:57.190 --> 00:51:58.840
We're like, upstream downstream.

00:51:58.840 --> 00:51:59.840
Should have used bednet.

00:51:59.840 --> 00:52:00.770
Should have used a condom.

00:52:00.770 --> 00:52:01.530
Should have done this.

00:52:01.530 --> 00:52:02.460
Should have done that.

00:52:06.210 --> 00:52:11.350
History has shown us that
we do that way too often.

00:52:11.350 --> 00:52:14.320
And so we can do
downstream-- that is,

00:52:14.320 --> 00:52:17.050
take good care of people-- as
we're doing upstream-- that is,

00:52:17.050 --> 00:52:19.020
prevent people
from getting sick.

00:52:19.020 --> 00:52:23.940
And that's an important thing
to get across to world leaders

00:52:23.940 --> 00:52:24.650
as well.

00:52:24.650 --> 00:52:25.990
This is complicated, you know?

00:52:25.990 --> 00:52:29.590
And they want something simple
or low cost or cost effective.

00:52:29.590 --> 00:52:30.910
And all these things change.

00:52:32.600 --> 00:52:34.950
Something that's
complex becomes simple.

00:52:34.950 --> 00:52:37.460
Something that is costly
becomes less costly.

00:52:37.460 --> 00:52:39.120
Something that is
effective becomes

00:52:39.120 --> 00:52:41.490
replaced by something
that's far more effective.

00:52:41.490 --> 00:52:45.070
And again, the bureaucracies
can't move rapidly enough.

00:52:45.070 --> 00:52:49.760
That's, again, why
we need room to move,

00:52:49.760 --> 00:52:52.210
and that requires resources.

00:52:52.210 --> 00:52:54.460
Against, [INAUDIBLE]
systems, blah, blah, blah.

00:52:54.460 --> 00:52:58.620
And that's very hard, I
think, for world leaders.

00:52:59.980 --> 00:53:03.800
They're being told, here's your
budget, or here's your plan.

00:53:03.800 --> 00:53:06.810
In fact, you get
derided for wanting

00:53:06.810 --> 00:53:09.730
to change as fast
as the pathogens do.

00:53:09.730 --> 00:53:11.870
You get made fun of.

00:53:11.870 --> 00:53:14.950
Which is imprudent, as
we're now seeing with ebola.

00:53:14.950 --> 00:53:15.950
That's a great question.

00:53:15.950 --> 00:53:18.449
JACQUELINE FULLER: Why don't
we have our last two questions?

00:53:18.449 --> 00:53:20.284
Just both of you
ask your questions

00:53:20.284 --> 00:53:21.950
one right after each
other, and that way

00:53:21.950 --> 00:53:23.908
we can get them in before
[INAUDIBLE] take off.

00:53:24.799 --> 00:53:25.340
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:53:26.390 --> 00:53:28.930
For those who are
surviving ebola,

00:53:28.930 --> 00:53:31.160
there's obviously a
huge amount of stigma.

00:53:31.160 --> 00:53:34.100
And I'm just wondering how the
health systems in West Africa

00:53:34.100 --> 00:53:35.225
are treating the survivors.

00:53:36.300 --> 00:53:40.540
PAUL FARMER: Well,
I don't know enough.

00:53:40.540 --> 00:53:49.110
But, again, to quote Jim Kim, we
should hire every one of them.

00:53:49.110 --> 00:53:50.900
I think that's exactly
the right logic.

00:53:50.900 --> 00:53:56.070
And the health care systems
and the neighborhoods,

00:53:56.070 --> 00:53:59.790
neighborhood organizations,
church groups,

00:53:59.790 --> 00:54:01.777
whatever-- I think
that's really going

00:54:01.777 --> 00:54:03.360
to be an important
message to get out.

00:54:03.360 --> 00:54:06.790
And I'm quite sure that's why
Jeffrey Wright was working

00:54:06.790 --> 00:54:10.850
not just to get people in
the United States or Europe

00:54:10.850 --> 00:54:14.300
who might see one of his movies.

00:54:14.300 --> 00:54:16.242
And, again, I don't
know-- I guess

00:54:16.242 --> 00:54:17.700
that's a kind of
global phenomenon.

00:54:17.700 --> 00:54:18.990
I messed up again.

00:54:18.990 --> 00:54:20.710
But also to get
the message of hope

00:54:20.710 --> 00:54:26.820
out in areas facing big
burdens of ebola disease.

00:54:26.820 --> 00:54:29.710
So I think that's just
unfurling right now,

00:54:29.710 --> 00:54:31.840
and that we would
do well, all of us,

00:54:31.840 --> 00:54:34.330
including those of us who
are going to be working there

00:54:34.330 --> 00:54:39.470
for some time, to keep on
underlining how much we need

00:54:39.470 --> 00:54:42.120
the survivors to be
part of the solution,

00:54:42.120 --> 00:54:45.010
and that we're with them.

00:54:45.010 --> 00:54:48.150
And I'm hoping that'll
change very rapidly.

00:54:48.150 --> 00:54:50.230
And the health systems--
again, remember

00:54:50.230 --> 00:54:52.900
the health systems are
underfunded and collapsed,

00:54:52.900 --> 00:54:56.430
so they couldn't just say, OK,
we'll hire all of them, right?

00:54:56.430 --> 00:54:57.342
But we could.

00:54:57.342 --> 00:54:59.800
We could help them do that and
strengthen the public health

00:54:59.800 --> 00:55:03.762
system by a relatively
minor expense, right?

00:55:03.762 --> 00:55:05.220
One little happy
thing-- and I know

00:55:05.220 --> 00:55:07.660
you wanted both
questions to be asked--

00:55:07.660 --> 00:55:11.680
is that when I was
leaving Monrovia,

00:55:11.680 --> 00:55:15.190
they were just opening up
a new ebola treatment unit.

00:55:15.190 --> 00:55:19.809
And the they was the Liberians,
and working with colleagues

00:55:19.809 --> 00:55:20.600
mostly from Uganda.

00:55:22.080 --> 00:55:26.590
And it was the day
before the grand opening,

00:55:26.590 --> 00:55:33.655
and there was a huge crowd in
front of the ebola treatment

00:55:33.655 --> 00:55:35.715
unit, and they were volunteers.

00:55:35.715 --> 00:55:37.735
And it was all Liberians.

00:55:40.560 --> 00:55:41.670
People want to help.

00:55:43.303 --> 00:55:45.850
And we've got to help
them help, right?

00:55:45.850 --> 00:55:48.777
Because they have
resources we don't have,

00:55:48.777 --> 00:55:50.360
but we have resources
they don't have,

00:55:50.360 --> 00:55:52.080
and I think it's going to be
the same with the survivors.

00:55:52.080 --> 00:55:52.890
JACQUELINE FULLER:
OK, last question.

00:55:52.890 --> 00:55:54.056
PAUL FARMER: Great question.

00:55:54.492 --> 00:55:56.450
AUDIENCE: I have a couple
of questions on the--

00:55:56.450 --> 00:55:58.283
JACQUELINE FULLER: No,
you get one question.

00:55:58.830 --> 00:56:02.340
AUDIENCE: On the
disease ebola itself.

00:56:02.340 --> 00:56:04.640
You mentioned that the
survival rate is very low,

00:56:04.640 --> 00:56:07.430
because the treatment
options are not that good.

00:56:07.430 --> 00:56:11.790
Do we know the growth room for
how much better the survival

00:56:11.790 --> 00:56:15.105
rate could be if we had
good treatment options?

00:56:16.170 --> 00:56:19.090
And the second
question is I've seen

00:56:19.090 --> 00:56:21.690
all these pictures of
people in space suits.

00:56:21.690 --> 00:56:23.460
Is that an overabundance
of caution,

00:56:23.460 --> 00:56:25.380
or is ebola really
that infectious?

00:56:25.380 --> 00:56:26.250
JACQUELINE FULLER:
That's a good question.

00:56:26.250 --> 00:56:27.583
PAUL FARMER: Two good questions.

00:56:27.583 --> 00:56:28.261
He was right.

00:56:28.261 --> 00:56:30.260
JACQUELINE FULLER: And
you can answer them both.

00:56:30.260 --> 00:56:32.560
PAUL FARMER: Well,
I don't believe

00:56:32.560 --> 00:56:33.935
it's an overabundance
of caution.

00:56:35.870 --> 00:56:41.120
And just to say one reason why,
and then I'll go to the other.

00:56:42.980 --> 00:56:48.160
It's one thing to wear this gear
in an air conditioned building,

00:56:48.160 --> 00:56:48.660
right?

00:56:49.770 --> 00:56:52.840
And even in the New
York Times article

00:56:52.840 --> 00:56:55.320
a couple days ago about
Nigeria's response,

00:56:55.320 --> 00:56:57.590
they mentioned air
conditioned hospitals.

00:56:57.590 --> 00:57:02.730
And in Haiti, when
I'm about to pass out,

00:57:02.730 --> 00:57:06.780
I go into the surgery wing,
because it's air conditioned.

00:57:06.780 --> 00:57:08.770
I mean, really, pass out.

00:57:08.770 --> 00:57:13.802
Now, there's no
electricity, so how's

00:57:13.802 --> 00:57:15.260
there going to be
air conditioning?

00:57:15.260 --> 00:57:20.800
Here and there,
maybe, but how long

00:57:20.800 --> 00:57:23.375
can you wear that
and be very careful?

00:57:25.420 --> 00:57:30.575
The people I trust
most say about an hour,

00:57:30.575 --> 00:57:31.575
and then its disposable.

00:57:32.830 --> 00:57:34.600
Now, there must be
other solutions.

00:57:35.790 --> 00:57:39.230
We need to talk to manufacturers
who understand this.

00:57:39.230 --> 00:57:41.400
It's too hot, right?

00:57:42.910 --> 00:57:44.880
And what does that
mean, it's too hot?

00:57:44.880 --> 00:57:47.490
You make a mistake,
you get careless,

00:57:47.490 --> 00:57:51.740
you don't have on
the right coverage,

00:57:51.740 --> 00:57:55.180
it's because people look at
a video at how often people

00:57:55.180 --> 00:57:58.500
touch their eyes or their mouth.

00:57:58.500 --> 00:58:02.820
It's not that it's suddenly
going through skin.

00:58:02.820 --> 00:58:06.320
So I don't think it's
an excess of caution

00:58:06.320 --> 00:58:09.790
until we have the
staff and the stuff we

00:58:09.790 --> 00:58:11.545
need to make it
go very smoothly.

00:58:13.400 --> 00:58:18.430
So the other point, which I'm
very passionate about, is--

00:58:18.430 --> 00:58:24.720
this is just me saying
live to the planet,

00:58:24.720 --> 00:58:26.287
or wherever this stuff goes--

00:58:26.287 --> 00:58:27.870
JACQUELINE FULLER:
Live to the planet.

00:58:27.870 --> 00:58:28.536
Thanks, YouTube.

00:58:29.650 --> 00:58:32.730
PAUL FARMER: I
think that we should

00:58:32.730 --> 00:58:38.270
assume that we are able to save
the great majority of people

00:58:38.270 --> 00:58:40.630
already sick with ebola.

00:58:40.630 --> 00:58:41.300
Why?

00:58:41.300 --> 00:58:45.540
What's the risk in
saying, 95% survival rate?

00:58:45.540 --> 00:58:47.600
Risk that I'll look like a fool?

00:58:47.600 --> 00:58:49.510
I don't care, right?

00:58:51.160 --> 00:58:54.870
I would like, as a physician
and as a community health

00:58:54.870 --> 00:58:57.910
activist-- I could care
less if that sounds

00:58:57.910 --> 00:59:00.980
foolish to any of my colleagues.

00:59:00.980 --> 00:59:07.620
If we assume that 95% of
people could be saved,

00:59:07.620 --> 00:59:11.640
and we-- pardon me, but bust
our asses to try and get them

00:59:11.640 --> 00:59:17.320
diagnosed and cared for early
on and do everything we can,

00:59:17.320 --> 00:59:21.910
what's the risk of having an
excess of zeal, as opposed

00:59:21.910 --> 00:59:23.890
to an excess of caution?

00:59:23.890 --> 00:59:30.240
So I think that message of
90% case fatality is damaging.

00:59:30.240 --> 00:59:31.620
I've heard it before.

00:59:31.620 --> 00:59:35.210
What's the case fatality rate
of untreated pneumococcal

00:59:35.210 --> 00:59:38.350
[INAUDIBLE] before we developed
antibiotics, or for those

00:59:38.350 --> 00:59:42.412
who live outside of the
antibiotic realm even today?

00:59:42.412 --> 00:59:43.370
It's probably the same.

00:59:43.370 --> 00:59:44.900
It's probably 90%.

00:59:44.900 --> 00:59:47.790
So I think we should
believe that we

00:59:47.790 --> 00:59:50.180
can flip those
numbers on their head.

00:59:52.280 --> 00:59:57.540
This is a failure of delivery
of basic supportive care.

00:59:57.540 --> 01:00:00.570
And when we address that, and
we say, oh, you were wrong,

01:00:00.570 --> 01:00:02.840
it's really 50%, that's fine.

01:00:02.840 --> 01:00:04.180
I can live with that.

01:00:04.180 --> 01:00:06.810
But until we address
the failure of delivery,

01:00:06.810 --> 01:00:09.220
I'm just going to
assume, based on what

01:00:09.220 --> 01:00:14.220
we know about the critically
ill from sepsis, whether it's

01:00:14.220 --> 01:00:18.360
of bacterial or viral cause,
or hemorrhagic complication,

01:00:18.360 --> 01:00:20.830
that we should be
saving everybody.

01:00:20.830 --> 01:00:23.590
And if it's not everybody's
job to save them,

01:00:23.590 --> 01:00:26.790
it is the job of
doctors and nurses

01:00:26.790 --> 01:00:28.540
and their family members, right?

01:00:28.540 --> 01:00:30.211
That's what their
family members are

01:00:30.211 --> 01:00:32.460
going to care about-- their
mothers and their siblings

01:00:32.460 --> 01:00:33.870
and their children.

01:00:33.870 --> 01:00:36.980
And we've made
this mistake before

01:00:36.980 --> 01:00:40.415
around every serious
infection I know of,

01:00:40.415 --> 01:00:43.025
or cancer like acute
leukemia in children.

01:00:45.110 --> 01:00:48.430
We've got to fight to
do that part of our job.

01:00:50.130 --> 01:00:50.950
Thank you.

